îíŸ@8be51c23febf4e3d37e3f7e88bb52b44ed52fa35890fb30f6f53ce54d311ea4c⁄ßTitle: Duration
Path: Duration
Content:
Description:

Represent a unit of a passage of time
Annotation:

``duration``

Literal Syntax:

A numeric (integer or decimal) literal followed immediately by a duration unit (listed below). E.g., 
``10sec``
, 
``987us``
, 
``-34.65day``

Casts:

[link: /commands/docs/into_duration.md] ``into duration``
See also:

[link: /book/types_of_data.md#durations] Types of Data - Durations
íŸ@387dd1ef273da2547319d36ddfcbb3550c2ff9ba4aab35d261e06d4055456657⁄Title: Duration
Path: Additional Language Notes
Content:
Durations are internally stored as a number of nanoseconds.
This chart shows all duration units currently supported:
Duration
Length
``ns``

nanosecond
``us``
/
``Œºs``

microsecond
``ms``

millisecond
``sec``

second
``min``

minute
``hr``

hour
``day``

day
``wk``

week
Datetime values can be combined with durations in calculations:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> (date now) + 1day

Tue, 13 Aug 2024 11:49:27 -0400 (in a day)

> 2024-08-12T11:50:30-04:00 - 2019-05-10T09:59:12-07:00

274wk 2day 22hr 51min 18sec

```
Months, years, centuries and millenniums are not precise as to the exact

number of nanoseconds and thus are not valid duration literals. Users are free to define

their own constants for specific months or years.
